Meshes.jl/blob/d927d5629f5f676684cb2b05ee35c4de9379938c/src/connectivities.jl#L99","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/46576/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/46576/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null},"comment":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1282703231","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/46576#issuecomment-1282703231","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/46576","id":1282703231,"node_id":"IC_kwDOABkWpM5MdH9_","user":{"login":"juliohm","id":3345261,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjMzNDUyNjE=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/3345261?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm","html_url":"https://github.com/juliohm","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/juliohm/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-10-18T16:54:02Z","updated_at":"2022-10-18T16:54:02Z","author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"> In short, a tuple of values is superior to a view with a tuple of indices. The only benefit the view offers is the ability to mutate the parent's contents.

@mikmoore I don't know if I understand what you mean.

Here is a concrete example:

```julia
points = rand(Point3, 100)

inds1 = (1,4,10,5) # tuple
inds2 = [1,4,10,5] # vector

@allocated view(points, collect(inds1)) # allocates 144
@allocated view(points, inds2) # allocates 48
```

Now imagine that I am taking these views thousands of times. If the view worked with tuple directly I could pass `inds1` as is to the view and avoid the allocations, which is what is happening with `inds2`. Now I need to convert Tuple to Vector manually using `collect` just to take a view.

What am I missing?","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1282703231/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}
